J=E2=80=99ai ajout=C3=A9 la d=C3=A9finition des poids de r=C3=A8gles dans B=
P3-help :

### Rule weight
=E2=80=A2 Each rule may be assigned a weight in the range 0..32767. These a=
re=20
used when there are multiple rules in the "RND", "LIN", "SUB" or "SUB1=E2=
=80=9D=20
grammars.
=E2=80=A2 The weight value is indicated between angle brackets, e.g. <43>.=
 The=20
default weight is 127. A rule with a weight of 0 is inactive.
=E2=80=A2 The probability of selecting a rule is the ratio of its weight to =
the=20
sum of the weights of the eligible rules (whose left argument is found=20
in the work string).
=E2=80=A2 Weights in the range 0..127 can be set using MIDI controllers and=
=20
parameters K1, K2, etc.
=E2=80=A2 Weights can be infinite and are notated as <inf>. A rule with an=
=20
infinite weight will always be included in the selected rules if its=20
left argument is found in the work string.
=E2=80=A2 Weights can be dynamically controlled: any rule can be given a=20
positive or negative weight increment each time it is applied. For=20
example, a rule with a weight of <100-30> will have successive weights=20
of 100, 70, 40, 10 and 0 and therefore cannot be applied more than four=20
times in the same production.

Un d=C3=A9tail important est que pour calculer la probabilit=C3=A9 d=E2=80=
=99une r=C3=A8gle il=20
faut diviser son poids par la somme des poids des r=C3=A8gles CANDIDATES, q=
ui=20
n=E2=80=99est donc pas n=C3=A9cessairement la somme des poids dans la sous-=
grammaire.=20
=C3=87a se passe =C3=A0 la  ligne 1307 dans =E2=80=9CCompute.c=E2=80=9D. Do=
nc la probabilit=C3=A9 peut=20
changer m=C3=AAme si le poids est statique.

Par exemple, dans cette grammaire :

ORD
S --> A B C
=E2=80=94=E2=80=94
RND
<1> A --> a a
<1> B --> b b
<1> C --> c c

la probabilit=C3=A9 de la r=C3=A8gle choisie =C3=A9tait de 1/3 puis 1/2 pui=
s 1/1.

=E2=80=94=E2=80=94

Je reviens sur SUB et sur cet exemple :

SUB
gram#1[1] S --> A B B A B B A
gram#1[2] A B --> a B
gram#1[3] B A --> B b
gram#1[4] B B A --> B e A
gram#1[5] B B --> f B

dont voici la trace :

[Step #1] Selected: gram#2[1] S --> A B B A B B A
[Step #2] Selected: gram#1[2] A B --> a B
[Step #3] Selected: gram#1[5] B B --> f B
[Step #4] Selected: gram#1[4] B B A --> B e A

Rule already selected: gram#1[2] A B --> a B
[Step #5] Selected: gram#1[2] A B --> a B

Rule already selected: gram#1[5] B B --> f B
[Step #6] Selected: gram#1[5] B B --> f B

Rule already selected: gram#1[4] B B A --> B e A
[Step #7] Selected: gram#1[4] B B A --> B e A

[Step #8] Selected: gram#1[3] B A --> B b

R=C3=A9sultat =3D a f e a f e b

Tout se passe comme si toutes les r=C3=A8gles candidates =C3=A9taient appli=
qu=C3=A9es=20
en m=C3=AAme temps. En r=C3=A9alit=C3=A9, elles sont lues dans l=E2=80=99or=
dre (l=E2=80=99ordre =C3=A9tant=20
arbitraire) et choisies dans l=E2=80=99ordre croissant de la position de=20
d=C3=A9rivation de gauche =C3=A0 droite. C=E2=80=99est pourquoi la r=C3=A8g=
le [5] est appliqu=C3=A9e=20
avant la r=C3=A8gle [4].

Voir le dessin en PJ qui illustre les =C3=A9tapes de d=C3=A9rivation.

Je le comprends intuitivement mais je ne saisis plus bien la logique=20
dans FindCandidateRules() de =E2=80=9CCompute.c=E2=80=9D.

Je vais r=C3=A9=C3=A9tudier SUB1.

